Before today, I haven&#8217;t written in this journal for seven months. By now no one reads it, yet I have a desire to write in it. Why? Why do people write in journals for everyone to read? Isn&#8217;t it a bit conceited? Well, we all know by now that I am conceited, so I&#8217;m not going against any principle and can proceed.

I can&#8217;t remember the last time I&#8217;ve procrastinated to such a degree. I did one item of homework this weekend, and only because it was an easy extra-credit substitute for a harder assignment. I have a final draft due for a paper tomorrow, and have I done it? Nooooo. Why not? A loophole. Here it is&#8230; The final draft is due Monday for student critiquing. The final FINAL draft is due then Wednesday. What will I do about what&#8217;s due tomorrow? One of two things: either write a very poor piece that I wound&#8217;t really consider turning in, or plead with my professor for mercy. It will probably turn out to be a mixture of both. 

Now you&#8217;re wondering, &#8220;Andy! How could you be so irresponsible! I thought more of you.&#8221; Well, you&#8217;re right. You did think more of me. However, I do have a scapegoat for my irresponsibility. Laziness. It&#8217;s totally not my fault that I didn&#8217;t get it done. I have a disease. I cannot be held responsible for my actions; it was my state of laziness. &#8220;I&#8217;m sorry, Amy, I couldn&#8217;t get the paper done, I was lazy at the time.&#8221;

Hmm&#8230;
